title: Tripartite co-operation effective in safeguarding public health (with photos)
content_text:
p>
    Health authorities of the Mainland, Hong Kong and Macao have established a 
    solid and effective co-operation mechanism in safeguarding public health of 
    the three places, the Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, said 
    today (November 6) at the opening ceremony of the Seventh Joint Meeting of 
    Senior Health Officials of the Mainland, Hong Kong and Macao held in 
    Hangzhou. "Throughout the years, co-operation among the three places has extended from 
    the prevention and control of infectious diseases to collaboration on all

the prevention and control of infectious diseases to collaboration on all 
    fronts. We had active discussion on public health issues including our 
    preparedness for influenza pandemic. We will continue to maintain close 
    co-operation and communication among the three places, and work for the 
    greater well-being of our people," he said. Dr Chow shared with the meeting the work of the Hong Kong side in medical, 
    public health and food safety. Issues on the medical and health side, included influenza vaccination 
    subsidy scheme introduced this month, elderly healthcare voucher pilot

subsidy scheme introduced this month, elderly healthcare voucher pilot 
    scheme to be launched in January next year, free pneumococcal vaccination 
    for infants, fostering public-private partnership and launching the second 
    stage of public consultation on healthcare reform in the first half of next 
    year. On food safety, Dr Chow talked about the handling of mainland milk products 
    tainted with melamine. These included legislating on the safety standard of 
    melamine in food, stepping up sampling tests, submitting legislation to the 
    Legislative Council to empower the Government to make administer orders to

Legislative Council to empower the Government to make administer orders to 
    prohibit the import and supply of problem food, and direct that food 
    supplied be recalled. Topics of discussion at the meeting included preparedness against influenza 
    pandemic, Sanlu infant formula incident, the implementation of Co-operation 
    Agreement on Response Mechanism for Public Health Emergencies, and rescue 
    and post-quake reconstruction work in Sichuan.  The Mainland delegation of the Seventh Joint Meeting of Senior Health

Officials of the Mainland, Hong Kong and Macao was led by the Vice-Minister of Health, Professor Huang Jiefu; while the Macao Special Administrative Region delegation was headed by the Director of Health Bureau, Dr Lei Chin Ion. Ends/Thursday, November 6, 2008
Issued at HKT 11:38
